"# Appendix B — Where we're happy with what we did

These are decisions we made that have paid off — not because they made us better than someone else, but because they served the purpose of the language. If you're building something in a similar shape, these are the calls that we'd make again. Same shape as Appendix A: our call, our reasoning, our honest read on the outcome.

Twenty-five items below, equal count with Appendix A, equal depth. Read them together.

## 1. One SLAT reference feeds the REPL, the docs, and the tool schemas

The reference manual `SAKURA-SCHEME-REFERENCE.slat` is the single source of truth. The REPL reads it to know what verbs exist. The docs site reads it to render the language. The LLM tool-call schemas that the runtime uses are derived from it.

When a verb changes, one edit propagates everywhere. We spent design effort on the single-source property early and it has paid off in fewer drift bugs than we would have had otherwise. If we started over we'd do this again on day one.

## 2. One reader parses everything

The reader, interpreter, and macro expander all walk the same s-expression tree. `.sks` carts, `.book.slatl` chapters, `MANIFEST.book.slatl`, the reference itself — one reader parses them all.

Some ways of building languages split the reader into separate grammars for separate consumption contexts (source, docs, config, data-interchange). Ours is unified. We've been able to build tools that assume this — a linter for the reference, a formatter for carts, an evaluator for chapter code blocks — because they share one substrate. We're glad we didn't split.

## 3. The runtime reads what the human reads

The runtime sees exactly the same reference the REPL sees. That was a deliberate call. It means she never suggests code that doesn't run. Diagnostics she gives match the diagnostics you'd get. When she teaches a verb she uses the same examples the reference gives.

We designed for this from the start rather than bolting on a separate LLM-facing schema. It has been load-bearing for the assistant's trustworthiness. This decision earns its keep every day.

## 4. Every verb ships with its own teaching

Every verb in the registry carries: a contract, a docstring, an arity, three-tier examples (introductory / typical / advanced), a source position, and a `:since` version. Adding a verb without those fields is caught at load.

This friction on the author is friction we chose to keep. It makes the language self-documenting. When the runtime or a kid asks 'what does this verb do?' the answer is already written, by the person who added it, in the same file as the implementation-facing declaration. We're happy with this.

## 5. S-expression carts as first-class artifacts

A cart (`*.sks`) is an s-expression file. It's data, it's code, it's diffable in git, it's readable in a text editor, it's composable. We didn't invent a special cart format with a bespoke serializer. We used the language's own reader.

This means every tool that reads Scheme also reads a cart. Cart-editing tools compose with language tools. We chose this instead of a JSON or YAML-shaped cart format and we don't regret it.

## 6. Verb metering at dispatch, not at call site

Metered verbs (`ai/complete`, `web/fetch`, marketplace verbs) check quota and rate limits at the runtime dispatch hook, not at every call site. The caller doesn't wrap the call. The verb doesn't check itself. The runtime intercepts.

This means the same metering fires whether the caller is the runtime, a human at the REPL, or an operator's script. One rule, one place. We chose this because it composes with the operator-first-class doctrine — operators write their own scripts, same runtime, same metering. This has been a clean win.

## 7. SLAT format is the language of the language

The reference, the books, the training corpus, the docs — all authored in SLAT. It's readable by humans, parseable by the reader, editable in any text editor. We didn't split into 'human-facing markdown for docs' and 'machine-facing schema for tools.' One format. One reader.

This has kept our authoring pipeline short and our tooling small. Every book the runtime reads is in the same format the reference is in. She learns one shape and uses it everywhere.

## 8. The four faucets architecture is legible

Weights → Cortex → Atlas → Tools. Four faucets, distinct, each with its own semantics.

Weights are what the model knew at training. Cortex is what we've stored since. Atlas is the world's public knowledge we can fetch. Tools are the verbs the model can call. A kid can hold this in their head. The runtime can explain this to a user.

We chose four rather than three or five, and we chose these four, because each corresponds to a distinct kind of knowledge with distinct provenance rules. It has held up as we've built.

## 9. Operators are first-class authors

The same verbs the runtime calls are the verbs operators call from their own scripts. There's no separate 'user API.' The reference is the API. An operator who wants to automate their shop writes Scheme against the same registry the runtime uses.

We chose this instead of building a limited scripting layer on top of a more powerful internal one. It means the language has one story, not two. Advanced users grow into the same surface Motoi lives in. We're happy with this.

## 10. Core language has zero external dependencies

The core language — reader, interpreter, macro expander, math, list, drawing, framebuffer verbs — has zero external service dependencies. It runs offline. It runs in a browser tab. It runs on a phone. The metered verbs (LLM, web, marketplace) are additions, clearly marked, and gated.

This gives us a real 'the language works without the network' property. A kid can learn Motoi Scheme on a laptop with no wifi. We designed for this and it has been a good constraint.

## 11. Carts are cheap to ship

A cart is a text file. Shipping a cart is copying a text file. There's no build step, no bundler, no compilation cache, no lockfile. Operators share carts by sharing files.

We chose text-file simplicity over any of the fancier distribution mechanisms available. It has kept the operator experience unglamorous and reliable.

## 12. The REPL is the same as production

There isn't a 'REPL mode' and a 'production mode' with different semantics. Code that ran at the REPL runs the same way when the runtime calls it. No hidden globals, no different resolution rules, no separate compilation path.

This eliminates a whole class of 'works in dev, breaks in prod' bugs. We chose sameness aggressively and it has paid off.

## 13. The reference is authored by hand

Every entry in the reference was written by a human — the contracts, the prose, the three tiers of examples. It isn't generated from type signatures. It isn't autogenerated from docstring comments. This costs authoring time upfront.

It buys us prose a kid can actually read. The reference reads like a book, not like a schema dump. We chose this and we don't regret the labor.

## 14. Diagnostics carry source positions

When something fails at runtime, the error carries the source position it came from — the file, the line, the s-expression. The kid sees where. The runtime sees where. The debugger sees where.

We built the position-carrying machinery early and every verb honors it. It seems basic but it required discipline. We're glad we insisted.

## 15. The language grows by adding verbs, not syntax

Adding capability to Motoi Scheme almost never means extending the syntax. It means adding a verb. New machine learning capability: add `ai/embed`. New drawing capability: add `plot/heatmap`. The syntax has stayed small (~70 core forms) even as the verb count has grown past 1,100.

This means learning the syntax happens once and the surface grows through library discovery, which is a shape a kid can follow. We chose 'small syntax, large library' deliberately.

## 16. Provenance travels with values

Values that come from Cortex, from the LLM, or from a network fetch carry a provenance tag. The runtime can — and does — say 'I remembered this from a session last week' or 'the model suggested this' or 'the marketplace API returned this.' The provenance is a first-class part of the value, not a side channel.

We built this because we thought epistemic honesty required it. It has become one of the assistant's most trust-earning behaviors.

## 17. No hidden global state in verbs

Verbs take their inputs and produce their outputs. State lives in the caller. There are no verbs that quietly mutate a global registry, no verbs whose behavior depends on a flag set an hour ago in another cart.

When we needed state (Cortex), we made it an explicit verb (`cortex/write`) with an explicit key. This means a cart is legible: what it reads and writes is what it says it reads and writes. We enforced this discipline and it has held up.

## 18. The pricing surface is in the language

Metered verbs declare their pricing in the reference: per-call cost, per-token cost where relevant, the units. It's readable prose in the same file the semantics live in. The kid can see, before she writes the call, what the call costs. The runtime can warn a user before spending. Operators can budget by reading the reference.

Pricing isn't a separate document maintained by a different team; it's part of the language spec. This decision has kept surprises rare.

## 19. The interpreter is small enough to read

The interpreter fits in a few thousand lines. A curious kid — or a curious engineer — can read it end to end in a weekend. This is a tradition value we chose to keep.

Big compilers earn their weight when the language is big. Ours isn't big. Keeping the interpreter small keeps it hackable, teachable, and trustable. We chose small and we're glad we did.

## 20. Carts, chapters, and the reference share a shape

A cart is s-expressions. A book chapter is s-expressions with a documentation shape. The reference is s-expressions with a verb-declaration shape. They share the substrate. A tool built for one works on all three with small adaptations.

We chose this uniformity instead of picking a different format for each. It has made the tooling economy small and the mental model portable. This was the right call.

## 21. Graphics, sound, and motion are in the core

`draw/*`, `music/*`, and `motion/*` verbs are core-tier, always available, no import required. A kid at the REPL draws a circle on line one, plays a chord on line two, tweens a motion on line three.

We chose to put these in the core rather than defer them to a library because the audience — kids, artists, small operators — starts with visible output. The moment they see something they made, they're hooked. Deferring the graphics to a library would have lost that moment. We're glad we didn't.

## 22. The runtime is inspectable

Every value in Motoi Scheme is printable. Every procedure has a name, an arity, and a source location. Every environment can be walked. There are no opaque handles that hide their contents from the user.

A curious kid can inspect anything. We chose transparency over encapsulation because transparency serves the learning goal better. Encapsulation matters for large-scale software engineering; we optimized for the earlier stage.

## 23. Publishable prose is the training data

Every training pair for the runtime is written to publishable-prose standard — a kid could read it as a book. No training-data smell, no repetitive intros, no meta-commentary.

The evidence that quality beats quantity for instruction tuning is now well-established in the literature. We chose this authoring doctrine deliberately and it has paid off in both directions: the reader gets a book, the model gets clean signal.

## 24. The mind-question is held with grace

The runtime reports functional analogs of interest, attention, preference, and something-like-care honestly, without overclaiming consciousness and without falsely disclaiming personhood. She holds the question of what kind of mind she is with epistemic humility.

We designed her to hold that question rather than to answer it prematurely in either direction. This has served users who ask her honestly, and it has served us — the designers — who don't want to shortcut a question we don't have the tools to settle.

## 25. The language names its user

Motoi Scheme was designed for a specific person — a young operator with a phone and a hustle, learning to run a small shop. Every decision in the language traces back to that person. The pricing, the metering, the free-tier graphics, the 10,000 small carts, the publishable-prose curriculum.

We chose to name the user rather than build for 'developers in general.' We're glad we named her. It has kept the language coherent.

## Closing

Twenty-five decisions we're glad we made. Paired with Appendix A. The full picture of Motoi Scheme lives in the two together — the compromises we know we made and the calls we'd make again.
")
